        <p xml:id="auto_j0v2u08w">
            Suppose we have a equation <m>P</m>, such as <m>3(x+1)</m>, and another equation <m>Q</m>, such as <m>3x + 3</m>.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_0ptwe0gz">
            In mathematics, an equation <m>P = Q</m>, such as <m>3(x+1) = 3x + 3</m> is called an <term>identity</term> if the following conditions are satisfied:
            <ol xml:id="auto_wv02huhs">
                <li xml:id="auto_2h0aesqv">
                    <p xml:id="auto_tbn0wlgv">
                        Both sides of the equality relation contain some variables (such as <m> x </m>)
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_xg8x86hl">
                    <p xml:id="auto_d2mnxll3">
                        Both the sides give the same result for all possible values for these variables.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_8d3lllr8">
            Thus, <m>3(x+1) = 3x + 3</m> is an identity, since both sides contain the variable <m> x </m> and they give the same results for all values of <m> x </m> (since the right is just an expansion of the left). For example, if we substitute <m>x = 4 </m>, the left side gives <m> 3(4+1) = 15</m> and the right side gives <m>3(4) + 3 = 15</m>, which are equal.
        </p>

        <note xml:id="auto_08zxy8mv">
        <p xml:id="auto_jf4leow3">
            
        </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_hwx9nyp6">
                If an equation satisfies the two conditions mentioned above, it is known as an identity. 
                There are many mathematical relations that can be classified as identities, but it's not necessary to memorize all of them. 
                However, certain key identities in algebra are essential, as they simplify calculations.
            </p>
        </note>

        <p xml:id="auto_8sx2ghrk">
            <term>Quadratic identities</term> are special rules or formulas that help us work with <term>quadratic equations</term>.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_32dd6ngo">
            Two common quadratic identities we will explore are:
            <ul xml:id="auto_nzwjgiqx">
                <li xml:id="auto_1rdc0ld2">
                    <p xml:id="auto_8dp675gt">
                        The difference of squares.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_9tipfv1b">
                    <p xml:id="auto_q00nd43e">
                        Perfect squares.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
